        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer15542638" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17976334762850326822">Interesting how this book compares with another Pulitzer Prize winner I read recently -- Tarkington&apos;s <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/127028.The_Magnificent_Ambersons__The_Growth_Trilogy___2_' title='The Magnificent Ambersons (The Growth Trilogy, #2) by Booth Tarkington' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Magnificent Ambersons</a>. Each is a story of the great love a mother has for her son, and each is set in the &apos;early&apos; years of a fast-growing, developing American city (Chicago in this instance), yet the stories are very different from each other, as are the mothers. The sons do have quite a bit in common, but in general the characters in <i>So Big</i> are not only more likable but more realistic. Desp</span>
  <span id="freeText17976334762850326822" style="display:none">Interesting how this book compares with another Pulitzer Prize winner I read recently -- Tarkington's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/127028.The_Magnificent_Ambersons__The_Growth_Trilogy___2_" title="The Magnificent Ambersons (The Growth Trilogy, #2) by Booth Tarkington" rel="nofollow noopener">The Magnificent Ambersons</a>. Each is a story of the great love a mother has for her son, and each is set in the 'early' years of a fast-growing, developing American city (Chicago in this instance), yet the stories are very different from each other, as are the mothers. The sons do have quite a bit in common, but in general the characters in <i>So Big</i> are not only more likable but more realistic. Despite one or two sentimental passages that aren't my thing at all, I did enjoy Ferber's writing.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17976334762850326822" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

